,Recommended,238320,9367072,"Posted: 6 March, 2014",all,Guy in the Chair,"The GameOutlast is incredible! It's a horrifying, psychologically-driven, intense game of survival as you, Miles Upshur, try to escape Mount Massive Asylum (and find out what happened there). What most of you are probably wondering is this: ""Is it scary?"" YES, scary like no other game before it. It does use jump scare tactics, but don't let that discourage you. There's much more to Outlast's fear than that. One thing to note: the game's ending won't please everybody. It leaves a lot of things unexplained. I thought it was a well-done, open-ended conclusion, but no matter what you think of Outlast's ending, the journey there is definitely worth experiencing. 9.5/10.The DLCOutlast: Whistleblower is this game's pièce de résistance. I'm not sure if I'd say it's better, but it's definitely more well-done in many respects. Whistleblower helps to clarify a few key plot points that weren't explained in the main game. Here you play Waylon Park, the source within Mount Massive that tipped off Miles, the original game's protagonist, to the horrors going on within the asylum. Whistleblower works as both a prequel, showing what happens leading up to Miles' arrival at Mount Massive, and a sequel, showing what happens after the ending of the original game. And there's so much fear to be had in between those two points. I'd venture to say that Whistleblower is scarier than the base game, but its extreme use of graphic, unsettling content (moreso than the base game) doesn't sit well with some. You be the judge. The DLC also opens up some new plot points and then fails to even address a couple of them. This is my only problem with Whistleblower, but it isn't a huge one. If you're going to get the game, get the DLC along with it or you're going to missing out on a lot. Also: the ending to Whistleblower is great and answers the burning question we all had about the base game's ending (and then some). 9.5/10."
