76561198037077800,Not Recommended,238320,32262516,Posted: 8 June,all,dystopicfilms,"Hate me if you must, but I just could not get into ""Outlast"" no matter how hard I tried.It's not because I wasn't impressed with the graphical content of the game or the immersive atmosphere. On the contrary, both those things are a major plus in my view and continue to be. My problem with it though is the game's dynamic. I'm all for Stealth-Horror gaming. I am. ""Forbidden Siren"" is one of my favourite Horror games of all time and that's all about stealth. However, there isn't really that much to elevate ""Outlast"" above the the rest of the pack in this regard, at least not in my view. The game is a simple case of open door, fumble around in the dark, cower in a locker while the lunatic looks for you and then edge your way out hoping in vain that he doesn't catch you.And, try as you might, the homicidal nutjobs almost always catch you, which would be fine if you could defend yourself somehow. Now I realise that there is a message at the start of the game telling you that your character isn't fighter. I get that. I get that in that sort of scenario most of us would be overwhelmed with fear and fly into a blind panic. However, in a game where you are being stalked by a host of crazies who want you dead and you are surrounded by potential weapons, you do tend to find it a little frustrating that you can't simplay pick up a lead pipe and cave the lunatic's brains in.It's probably also got a lot to do with the fact that, if you are going to make a stealth game, I think it makes more sense to make it in third person. First-person stealth games tend not to work very well in my experience because you really aren't doing very much in them so character detail is important to maintain audience interest.As I said, ""Outlast"" is great as an atmospheric experience and on those grounds alone, I know a lot of people love it. Me, not so much. I felt very similarly about SOMA as well, so I don't know...maybe it's just me?"
