,Recommended,238320,11159385,"Posted: 9 July, 2014",all,❤ D A D D Y ❤,"If you're looking for a good scare, Outlast is certainly the game for you. I cannot say enough good things about it. The atmosphere is phenomenal and extremely well put together. Paired with the music and sounds, it can't get any better.As for the actual gameplay, Outlast needs a little thinking involved. You shouldn't expect for everything to be clearly marked for you. Outlast does, however, get a little repetitive - grab your three items to unlock this or fix that and you advance, all the while a monster patient is lurking around. It can get to feel a little repetitive, but if you're like me, you won't exactly notice. You'll be too busy trying to keep yourself alive and complete the objective. One downfall I did notice, besides the repetitveness, was the length. I've realized that most modern horror games aren't incredibly long, and this game follows the rest. I do wish there was more story to find, more gameplay, and a change in pace - i.e. reduce the repetiveness and try something different with the flow of the game, which is something we can hope for in Outlast 2.Outlast was a terrifying experience for me. There are gruesome cutscenes, jumpscares, and chase scenes. The characters are certainly twisted individuals. You can almost feel the pain, fear, and adrenaline that rushes through Miles Upshur, the protagonist in the story. His emotions are very well conveyed to the player. Not only Miles's emotions, but the various patients' emotions, as well. Plot twists, unexpected events, perfectly conveyed emotion, and a fantastic story really add to the game's atmosphere.This is a game I will recommend one hundred times over. Very fantastic game with great features. It can certainly send chills up your spine."
,Recommended,238320,9466822,"Posted: 14 March, 2014",all,VictorSeven,"When I first saw Outlast, I was intrigued. In the midst of so many Slender clones and games full of cheap, ineffective jumpscares, I was craving a sense of depth with a horror game. I found that depth in Outlast.Taking the role of an investigative journalist acting on an anonymous tip, I entered Mount Massive Asylum and soon found myself creeping slowly through the seemingly abandoned wards, straining for any sounds beyond my own footsteps, jumping at my own shadow. The game's atmosphere is the best I've ever experienced, bar none. It forgoes the cheap horror tradition of relying on screams and musical stings, and instead uses your entire environment - creaking floorboards, closing doors, lightning and thunder, even distant, ragged breathing - to set you on edge and keep you there the entire time.The game is brilliantly rendered, with stunning visuals and graphic depictions that truly reinforce the feeling that you've just stepped into hell on earth. The effects of the game on the main character become more and more apparent, and you'll notice a few types of damage you sustain stay with you for the entire game. The broadness of the creativity I experienced in the multitude of different settings kept me guessing, and the changes in venue served to take me out of my comfort zone JUST when I thought I was beginning to calm down. The pacing was perfect.Gameplay was astonishingly spot-on. No glitches or bugs, and I was delighted to find that the main character, Miles, has a bit of parkour ability. Somebody put Mirror's Edge in a horror game? My character actually has a chance at running? I've never experienced that before, and the feeling of having a slight chance to survive while skillfully vaulting desks, hopping up to catch a ledge, and hanging out a window to avoid a pursuer, makes the experience both more terrifying and exhilarating when you narrowly escape with your life. The game makes you think, and if you forget to look up, you will die.The story was phenomenal. Mount Massive, even in the state of its decay, is a living, breathing thing. With characters such as Chris Walker, Rick Trager, Dr. Wernicke, the Twins, Father Martin, and the Walrider, I found myself morbidly curious about how they came to be, and was delighted to find many answers. The Notes and Documents system added a whole new dimension of depth that made many of these characters more than just ""the monster you run from."" Learning about Chris Walker's origins, his motivations, how the Walrider came to be, the project that put Rick Trager in charge of his own ward, the truth about Dr. Wernicke... the list goes on. There is so much information on the things you're running from that it begins to change your mind, and in some cases, you actually begin to understand some of these characters.Overall, this game is one of the most tense, terrifying experiences I've ever faced... and I'm tough to scare. Bravo, Red Barrels. I can't wait for the Whistleblower DLC. To see Let's Plays of Outlast, visit VictorSevenGames on YouTube. And buy this game!"
