,Recommended,238320,7989112,"Posted: 9 December, 2013",all,Sam Hamwich,"Games of the horror genre usually don't hold my attention well, (either because I find them a bit over the top in the scare department, or they are lacking in anything but jump scares).  Outlast however somehow manages to keep me playing, and feeling nervous at the same time.Before I go into any sort of detail let me place Outlast's concepts in 3 simple steps.Step 1- Give players an eerie atmosphere with a basic creepy concept, such as I don't know, say an insane asylum? (Wait this does work, trust me)Step 2- Tap into the human psych and our deep down fear of being chased and hunted and place them in an interactive story 20 inches from our faces.Step 3- Continue to attack that primal fear relentlessly until we actually have to put down the controller/keyboard/mouse.  Then make us come back so we can experience this thrill as soon as our heart rate settles down again.This shouldn't be a working formula for a good game, but for some reason, this works fantastic for Outlast.This basic bit of thought pattern is what I call the ""Outlast Effect""(Yes i have been using this term out of the game!) The best way to describe this sensation is when you turn out the last light in the basement and quickly run up the stairs because you can feel or sense something lurking in the dark behind you.Given the fact that your character is only equipped with a video camera, which can record the horrors you face( and also provides you with semi-good night vision), the action can get quite intense.Outlast often makes you feel like someone is watching you, and this is usually the case.  You always feel as if around every corner you'll get a nasty surprise or find someone who wants you dead.  Yes, there are a bunch of jump scares, but they are very well placed and they seem to be placed strategically rather than in obvious spots.  The true horror this game provides is during its countless chase scenes. The game mechanics can add to this sensation greatly if you choose to use them well.  You can spin your head to look backwards to see if the enemy chasing you is gaining ground, you can also dive through doors, turning quickly to slam it shut on your pursuers. You can hide under beds, in lockers and sneak through small cracks that you can barely squeeze through.  The ability to hide from the enemy makes it interesting as well, and the AI reacts quite well to finding you.  Early in the game they rarely check for you in the correct hiding spots but as the game progresses the enemies seem to act more randomly and tend to catch you hiding more often. The game mechanics work excellent in this setting as well.  The mental hospital provides small narrow corridors, which are perfect for providing you with a claustrophobic feeling once the bad guys start chasing.The sound in this game is fantastic, from your character's breathing when you are hiding, to the sounds of the mumbling maniacs pursing you down the narrow corridors.  The different types of enemies come with their own sounds, some of the larger baddies carry chains, and one even has a massive pair of scissors.  You can often hear muffled footsteps in a room close by, or echoes down long corridors.  The music is very well orchestrated to fit the tone of being helpless and it seamlessly fades in and out according the danger.The visuals are also done well, the graphics are on par with any of the newer releases and the animation is fantastic.  When learning around corners your hand can be seen pressing against the walls or doorframes.  These items may seem like small detail, but that's actually what makes a good game noticeable in my opinion.Overall this is a fantastic addition to anyone's steam library.  The story is a bit lacking and considering the action is all about hiding and fleeing rather than fighting it may not be for everyone.Outlast gets a 9/10, and a big thumbs up!SamHamwich out."
