,Recommended,238320,8407120,"Posted: 29 December, 2013",all,๖ۣۜR3BORN,"Outlast is a relatively well done survival-horror game which efficiently blends the thrills and chills in equal measure. However, while Outlast delivers an effective experience with the genre norm, it doesn't deviate from the set path for anything creative and unique. One can expect the usual set pieces, the usual enemies, and the overly used jump scares.Now, to be fair... I certainly had my fair share of scares throughout the game (most of which were creatively placed), but towards adventures end I had found myself becoming slightly frustrated and annoyed with the lack of creativity. It was the same set path, over and over. Find this, hide from one enemy, run away, repeat. Outlast's biggest issue is the lack of enemy unpredictability, as essentially every encounter is scripted and therefore predictable.That aside, Outlast is an extremely polished video game. The visuals are gorgous, realistic, and smooth. The audio is clear, crisp, and efficient at setting the mood. The use of the video recorder as night vision isn't anything new (and was a tad over-used), but was implemented and designed extremely well, and was definitely one of the games strongest aspects. Unfortunately Outlast is a short game, with limited (if at all), replayability.I would only recommend a purchase of the game if it is on sale and you're itching for a quick horror fix."
