76561198022308951,Recommended,238320,7835734,"Posted: 29 November, 2013",all,Leopard,"This game was awesome.Overall, I would describe it as more of a ""thriller"" than a ""horror"" game.  If you play a lot of horror games, you won't find this terribly scary.  However, if you have a low threshold for horror, you will probably find it quite gruesome.  It relies on gore and shock to get a reaction from the player, rather than pacing and imagination a la Amnesia: The Dark Descent.  There are also a lot of jumpscares, but they are spread out well enough that they don't become too predictable.While I didn't find this as scary as, say, the original Amnesia, I did find it extremely exciting.  There are no puzzles to solve in Outlast, so the gameplay never stalls due to some overly confusing puzzle.  It's easily the best-looking horror game I've ever played; the setting is very detailed and the levels are always interesting (particularly towards the end).  You'll be using a nightvision camera to see through most of the game; the camera effects are very well done and look fantastic.  There are also a ton of little details in the way your character moves and in the environment that add to the immersion.  The devs took their sweet time polishing this up, and it shows.The only thing I would knock this game for is being poorly optimized.  It uses the Unreal engine, which is quite old, yet I could only run it on medium/high settings (it goes from low to very high for reference), even though I have no problems running games like Bioshock Infinite and Skyrim maxed out.  Even on a mix of medium/high, I occasionally had dips in framerate in one of the larger levels, which was irritating.  I should point out that the game still looks great on medium, so this wasn't really a big deal.According to Steam I finished the game in 5.4 hours, but I'll definitely be replaying it.  I got this on sale for about $7 and it was totally worth it."
