,Recommended,238320,9201281,"Posted: 20 February, 2014",all,Ƥαωℓ 🐾,"Overall Score 7.5/10Wow, so the developers of this game should seriously think about careers in hollywood movie making. They really know how to set the tone. The motif is a silent hill-esque investigation style horror. You play as an investigative journalist armed with only your video camera and a tip that leads you into the abyss of a psychiatric asylum.I love the creativity behind this game. It can be difficult to conceptualize survival games this isn't basically a never ending quest for resources, dulled by knowledge of predictable mechanics and action points. Outlast breaks the mould, and excells in these areas. Admittedly some parts are predictable and the motif, although not a widely used one, still gives you an idea that can't be too far from the truth without adding aliens or sasquatch.Having said that, the game itself is far from predictable. You'll quickly learn you can't play this like other games, with the exception of reload which are batteries for your camera. You find documents along the way which lays out the story. You have an assortment of maneuvers that allow you to negotiate your environment, my favorite being the ability to slide through narrow gaps... that one will literally save your life ;)Movement doesn't feel sluggish however there does seem to be some slight hangtime when jumping. The graphics aren't the best in the world as post processing elements are basically stereoscopic and there is a constant, migraine inducing noise overlay which worsens tenfold during the use of your cameras nightvision. The textures aren't spectacular but they aren't distracting either, they do the job just fine. And in all honestly, you'll likely be too immersed in the game to notice many of the lacking elements, post processing and overlay excluded.Now as I understand, this game isn't optimized for 32bit systems and requires a workaround.In summary I'd recommend this game to friends and horror genre fans. Happy Gaming!"
