,Recommended,238320,8442869,"Posted: 30 December, 2013",all,MulletMaximus,"Not many a game has ever given me face-contorting , adrenaline fueled , panic rushes like Outlast . Actually, no game ever has . Never has a locker made me feel so safe, as if cradled by a loving mother ! Red Barrels have really mastered the horror genre in most aspects with Outlast . The camera being your only tool for survival , it's a nightmare on air . From running through blood drenched corridors with insane patients close behind wanting to gut you , to stealthily manuevering around a head-ripping goliath , this game is not for the faint of heart . If you are up for a fear filled adventure , this is the perfect pick . Will you brave the asylum and its patients in hopes of freedom or will insanity take a hold of you first !?  I would give Outlast a hefty 9/10 ."
,Recommended,238320,8709870,"Posted: 14 January, 2014",all,The Eater of Dreams,"Another horror game where you can only run and hide, Outlast doesn't do a whole lot that's new but it stands tall as a strong, polished game that's genuinely scary. Essentially Amnesia-style gameplay in a new setting, it's good-looking, well-designed and doesn't fall prey to many of the pitfalls that remove the horror from supposedly scary games - it knows when to use silence and emptiness to full effect and doesn't ramp up the action as the game progresses, barring the weak ending.Jump scares come often and can get predictable, and aren't the main strength of the game. It's the organic horror that comes from being stalked or looking for a hiding spot in a panic that really makes it memorable. The sheer gore and disturbing elements, including sexual overtones to the antagonists, are uniquely unnerving though they might alienate some players. Good horror doesn't need to be gruesome, after all.Fairly short and with a very weak final act much less compelling than the rest of the game, it's not for everyone, but is fine fuel for those who love the unmatched rush of feeling genuinely afraid."
