,Recommended,238320,7441509,"Posted: 21 October, 2013",all,AyJay,"Before I go forward, I need to start off with this:I didn't like Amnesia much at all.The story was interesting but the gameplay itself as well as the scare factor was, to me, very overhyped. The gameplay seemed very much minimal and out of body. The entire time I felt I was looking in, and was not much immersed at all. Add to that the scare factor was greatly exaggerated and well... I was left disappointed.And then I bought Outlast.While there are many things I love about this game, I do need to put out a few warnings:This game is really gory. Not much for the squeamish at all.This game becomes very intense. I had to break at points because I just got too freaked out, something that hasn't happened to me since being hounded down by Nemesis in RE3.I'll start off with the immersion.Even though you -know- you're another character, his background is left vague and the only true objective you have is ""survive”. In this sense, it really becomes easy for the player to integrate his or herself with the character. That YOU are being chased, that YOU are cramming yourself in a locker, breaths stuttering and heart pounding as the door to the room is broken in. It makes it a very real sensation. I suppose it also helps to see hands reaching out to interact with objects rather than them floating in midair as well.The second thing is the environment.Very eerie, creepy setting… and just about every little thing gets you. Floorboards creaking will leave you on-edge trying to determine if that was you, an enemy, or just those old floorboards. The lighting is also pretty dynamic and fantastic in this game, striking scattered chairs and disfigured faces leaving you with a feeling of uneasiness.But I would have to say the piece du resistance is the music. What a fantastic arrangement this game has. As enemies find you, a shrill shriek of horns and strings alert you that your presence has been noticed. As enemies wander around, low, lingering tones with the occasional, random rise reach your ears, lulling you into a calmed state as you adjust only to be jarred from it over and over. And when wandering around with a new objective, subtle notes run across your ears, masked by footsteps and creaking doors.If you're a horror nut, this is the game for you. If Amnesia just wasn't doing it for you, this will. And for $20, I couldn't ask for more."
