76561197971405924,Recommended,238320,7492586,"Posted: 27 October, 2013",all,Xanderfaulk,"Outlast puts most recent ""horror"" games to shame.Taking a leaf from games like Amnesia, Outlast puts us in the shoes of Miles Upshur; an investigative journalist who sneaks into Mount Massive Asylum after a tip mentions the horrific excperiments conducted inside the walls. He'll soon learn to regret entering this place of sheer and utter nightmare fuel; as the game becomes a desperate fight for survival and a dash for the exit.Outlast visually represents a Triple A title, with the minds of them behind the making; but its gameplay is similar to it's indie counterparts where combat is not an option. The game requires exploration, investigation that rewards us with further exposition of what is truly going on; aswell as more batteries for the camera you carry that is the only source of seeing in the pitch black hallways.Whether it's finding fuses, navigating vents or hiding from naked dudes with pipes; the game is a truly terrifying and polished experience; any issues such as a short length of about 7-9 hours and an abrupt ending; are for the most part shadowed by the exilirating thrill this game offers by combing  the best of the gaming worlds.Outlast raises the bar for every future horror game, indie or not. The developers are also talking about making the sequel ;)4/5"
