,Recommended,238320,13207930,"Posted: 2 December, 2014",all,(PoA) ¿Señor Santiágo?!,"Intense every step of the way.That's how best to describeOutlast.  DeveloperRed Barrelshas fulfilled the vision they had for this first-person survival horror game: to create an emotional and unforgettable experience.  I look forward to playing their future games.Under the broad umbrella of games that can be considered to have any kind of horror element, Outlast gameplay is closer to the subtlety of theAmnesiaseries than it is toF.E.A.R.orDead Island, because the player has no direct combat ability and is forced instead to rely on what survival mechanics the game offers.  In this case the only options are running and hiding.  Once in a while the AI disappoints, but most of the time it keeps you on your toes.  I can't say for sure whether AI gets smarter with higher difficulty since I stuck to ""Normal.""  There isn't much to say beyond this about mechanics or design; you'll quickly figure it out for yourself, if you can hang in there long enough to get past the first several scares!The game looks excellent, while not necessarily pushing the envelope for 2013 visual standards.  The audio & soundtrack are every bit as impressive as the graphics and prove for the millionth time that sound is crucial to any horror experience, be it film or game.  Outlast was blessedly bug-free and smooth for my entire playthrough.  My time played reflects a single playthrough on the easiest difficulty (Normal) of the main campaign.  After finishing, I felt no compulsion to explore harder difficulties or subject myself to that adrenaline rush again.  After all, I'm no horror genre aficionado, only an occasional visitor.  The story is enjoyable but super generic, pretty much pulled straight from similar genre films.  Depending on how quickly you progress, the campaign will feel short.  Not a big game.  I do not own and did not play theWhistleblowerDLC and so unfortunately can't comment on it.I recommendOutlastto any genre fans (obviously) and also to anyone looking for a quick rush the likes of which can only be provided by horror-survival.  Truly every step of the journey is a battle of will to keep going rather than save and exit.  As I said earlier, once you are inside for a bit and get the hang of the mechanics and AI behavior, the fear factor rapidly drops from debilitating to bearable--and by this I mean thepumping heart, rapid breathing, sweating palmsvariety of bearable.  It remains tense throughout, and I hate to think that even one person would miss out on the fun because they walked away after being startled once or twice.TIP: Don't waste any time while the camera is running, since you have limited battery life.TIP: Don't miss easy battery pickups due to being too rattled/rushed/careless to look around as you move through rooms."
