,Recommended,238320,1568790,"Posted: 15 September, 2013",all,Tundra Scorpion,"Outlast is a picture perfect example of everything done right in a horror game, making the player feel completely helpless and hunted in an environment that makes them feel uncomfortable with a looming sensation of something just around the corner. With 0% of the budget on combat, Outlast has been made completely immersive with subtle and frightening sound effects, disturbing visuals and perfected first-person animations.The story of Outlast begins with a midnight drive to a supposedly abandoned asylum following a tip from an anonymous lead, the player takes the role of investigative journalist Miles Upshur as he delves to uncover the sinister secrets of Mount Massive Asylum.Immediately upon entering the asylum the player gets a sensation of being watched, confined and exposed, setting them up for a start at the slightest bump, scratch or shed of movement seen from the corner of your eye. The atmosphere is perfected with high-quality graphics and sound assets, which build up in intensity until exploding in the players face in an intense climax of terror upon their first encounter with one of the asylums mutilated patients.As with any game, while Outlast is good there are some drawbacks that keep it from being perfect. Outlast's puzzle solving lacks variation, recycling the same old method of rushing to press a button or turn a valve while an enemy chases you. While contributing to the sensation of being hunted, re-using these kinds of encounters over and over with a lack of effective follow-up made the game feel largely repetitive and I felt took a large part out of the experience.Outlast has also unfortunatly indulged in the cheap shots that are jump scares, which require little-to-no buildup and I feel have no place in a true horror game as they only serve to provide opportunities for talentless hacks like pewdietard to overreact. In comparison with another terrifying game, Amnesia: The Dark Descent, which had no jump scares and instead relied completely on it's atmosphere to scare the player, this comparison proves to me that horror games worth their weight in gold do not need jump scares and should rely on their immersion, which is something that Outlast would have done very well.Finally, without giving away too much, the story felt rushed and incomplete in some places, which didn't leave a lasting impression on me and failed to avidly explain the reasoning behind the inhumane experiments in Mount Massive.So while Outlast is a very good game and a welcome addition to the horror genre, it suffered some flaws that kept it from living up to it's full potential.Amnesia: The Dark Descent remains the scariest game I've played."
