76561197976688119,Recommended,238320,11786929,"Posted: 19 August, 2014",all,Minghawk,"Amnesia popularised a relatively new sub-genre of horror game that focused, as horror really should, on being unable to confront your enemies and hoping that you'll never have to do so.  A wave of imitiators and screechy Youtube reaction videos followed as it became clear how cheap and easy this kind of thing could be to put together.So there's been a lot of dross, in other words, but the occasional gem.  Outlast gets the formula entirely right.  You're unarmed, sure, but physically capable:  you can sprint, vault over desks, clamber into vents, jump over broken floors, and generally conduct yourself as a reasonably healthy person would if they were being pursued by a nutcase.  The game emphasises your physical presence, down to the shadows you cast in front of you and your hands gripping the edges of walls when you're near them.Not the longest game around, but the right length for what it wants to do, it does admittedly wear out its bag of tricks a little before the end - you'll begin anticipating things rather than being surprised by them.  This is a very minor quibble, though, and is kind of inevitable with this sort of thing.Genuinely unsettling and occasionally very scary, this is how this kind of thing should be done."
