76561198025964278,Recommended,238320,31367094,Posted: 25 April,all,fish dimension,"*NO SPOILERS HERE*This game is scary. It doesn't cop out like so many others and rely purely on jumpscares. It puts you in a stressful situation, that often requires cat-like relfexes, and quick thinking. This is a great game, and I'll tell you why.Graphics: The graphics in this game are outstanding. The gritty realism and disgusting amounts of detail only intensify an already off putting experience. Whether it be detailed, high-resolution blood mixed with chunks of flesh leading you to the next change of pants, or the disturbing scars of the deformed residents of the now abandoned Mount Massive Asylum. The graphics were mindblowingly great in 2013, and they still hold up today. 9/10Sound: Good Lord, the sound in this game is good. Just the quality of every sound effect, the echos of water dripping onto the floor, the deranged mumbles and rantings of wonderfully voice acted mentally unstable scientific expirements, the heavy breathing and footsteps of the protagonist, Miles Upshur, as he runs from danger in the form of a madman. Just grab your favorite headphones and turn the volume up, and you're guaranteed to become immersed in the experience on a whole-new level. 10/10Gameplay/Fun to be had: This game is so much fun to play. The controls are responsive and oddly satisfying, despite how simple they are. The stressful, high-speed, escapes from the ugly, terrifying former inmates will pump adrenaline and fear through your veins as you vault over overturned desks, scramble into air vents just your pursuer grabs you, and slowly inch your way along ledges as you gaze down to the horrors below you. 8.5/10Story: This game has a great story on so many levels. It's obvious some serious thought, time, and effort was put into the writing of this game. The ending was a little disappointing, but I won't spoil anything. 8/10Overall: You don't just play Outlast. You experience it, and you have a blast doing so.9+10+8.5+8=35.5-----> 35.5/40"
