,Recommended,238320,7834233,"Posted: 29 November, 2013",all,AsphyxA,"You should play this with the lights off and your best headphones to really enhance the fear and horror this game will grace you with.Anyhow, this game wasn't particularily scary (except for the generic jump-scare) as it was stressful and had your pulse rise quite often. You often have to crawl through pitch black areas with only your camera's nightvision as your only source of light, and in many cases you also have to run from some ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ out to ♥♥♥♥ you up at the same time. So it's more of a stressful game of making quick decisions in a short amount of time than pure creepiness.Especially if you play it on Nightmare difficulty as you only are allowed to have a maximum amount of 2 batteries compared to Normal difficulty's 10 batteries.You end up mad-dashing through the majority of the game really, which is too bad as it doesn't leave room for enough exploring to satisfy me.Though the areas you had time to explore and really let them get to you had you in a tightened state all the way through. The music and soundeffects are really playing with your mind and when you think the threat is over it's often right around the next corner.The few areas where you really could let your fantasy play and enhance the horrors lurking the dark halls of Massive Mount Asylum had you on your toes the whole time. You can almost feel your heart rate rise in sync with the protagonist's when you encounter the deranged events of this game.All in all I'd say it was too stressful and had you miss out a lot of environmental exploration and general atmosphere as you most of the time dashed through the darkest places since your camera batteries were running out. But the places where you actually could play without the nightvision on really had you captivated and in a tight grip of fear!I'd recommend this game to anyone who wants a beautifully decent horror game."
