,Recommended,238320,12472838,"Posted: 12 October, 2014",all,Quibber123,"Outlast is an ""alright"" game. It is just short enough and delivers enough content to be recommended, but it only offers JUST enough to be recommended. With the major competition of this game being the far superior Penumbra and Amnesia games by Frictional Games it has quite a lot to live up to. Unfortunately the gameplay and ""horror"" are barely enough to hold the average player through. It goes for the jump scare route roughly 100% of the time. The jump scares themselves work the first and maybe the second time, but after you see it's a sub-par ""one trick pony"" there's no horror left in it only frustration. The enemies in this game do not follow the wonderful template set by Amnesia where they seemingly come and go as they please instead they follow a set path they patrol until you pass that area. Along with that the A.I. that they have is rather dodgy to when they actually see you and trying to hide from them can be a pain. I personally discovered that the easiest way to get past the enemy is to simply run past them the second they bust the door down instead of wasting time trying to hide. Once you run past them in most places where you have to go to make them disappear is in that room they came from. If you do try the hiding route expect to waste time dying for reasons that shouldn't happen and getting spotted in places that really don't make sense. None of that is scary. It's frustrating. A better game for jump scares is Doom 3. A better game for weaponless stealth horror would be Amnesia or Penumbra. A better game for crazy psychological/paranormal experiments is F.E.A.R. or Condemned. If it was the guts and gore that scared you even Dead Space is better for that. This game really only serves as a way to kill a few hours if you have a horror itch and have already played all of the above games. If you haven't then what are you waiting for!Overall I give it a 6/10."
