,Recommended,238320,33849198,Posted: 27 July,all,SKCJulz,"Before Outlast, I never played horror games. If Outlast had never come along, I may never have written such a passionate and heartful review. The story of this game is flawless, matching it with it's sensational graphics for the time, and even still today. The goriness of the game is a single spec in the pool of positivity that can be seen in this game. As previously stated, the story keeps you on the edge of your seat, and from passing out, until the very ending. There are multiple twists at every corner in the plot. The horror aspect is captured perfectly. While livestreaming, I had to pause multiple times because of the fright I felt while playing. Gameplay itself is honestly fine. The controls make sense and the overall objectives are fairly dificult. Overall a 10/10 game. No more perfect horror game that I can think of to date."
,Recommended,238320,8086213,"Posted: 17 December, 2013",all,Carth,"Similar to the film Grave Encounters, the game is set in some kind of mental institution and you are armed with only a digital camera with a nightvision toggle that consumes the batteries. The story is told through notes you make when you have the camera out and through documents you find strewn in the levels.It borrows from the Amnesia series in that you can't actually defend yourself against any of the unpleasant things you might encounter. Your only course of action is to run and to hide. However, whereas in Amnesia you might have had something chasing you and you knew it would kill you so you ran until you were safe with your heart pounding, in Outlast you are required to backtrack past the same enemy over and over. Far from being scary, it just becomes an annoyance.There are many sections where you need to find a key (or other item) but when looking for it you will be seen by an enemy, then you'll run, hide in a closet, wait for him to leave, then go and search again, the same thing happens, repeat ad nausem or until he finally kills you. The scariness is gone and it just becomes frustrating. You know what you have to do; you might even know where the key is, but you have to get past something that will chase you and instantly kill you.There is functionality to look over either shoulder using Q or E. It is not very useful though because it is disorienting. I suppose that was the intention: when running from something you take a quick glance over your shoulder and see it just behind you. The trouble is, in real life we are unaware of the movement of our head because our brain processes it for us. We don't see the world spin when we turn our head. When the game shows you everything spin it's not actually realistic, it's annoying and makes the ""look behind"" function not very usable.The need to use the camera with its night vision to see does add some tension, which is helped along by your character breathing heavily etc. There is an outdoor part which is reminiscent of The Blair Witch Project in its atomosphere.If you like horror games then this is worth a play. It has a great atmosphere and some nice visuals. There are a few jump scares and to start with it's quite immersive until the gameplay gets a bit samey and you know what the threats are. But by that time you'll probably see it through to the end to find out what happens. The game is about the right length in that respect."
