,Recommended,238320,8693812,"Posted: 13 January, 2014",all,mmm!5NATCH,"Your heart will be racing while 'Outlast' delivers an extremely thrilling experience.The 'first person horror' seems to be trendy at the moment but 'Outlast' is definitely a strong leader of this recent genre.If you're considering this game, but just not too sure what to expect, please read on...The story begins with our hero, Miles, a freelance journalist who gets a tip off to investigate an asylum that for many years had closed down but has recently opened up as a charity organisation. Curious to discover whats inside, Miles discovers the place has been over run by various inmates who are victims of scientific experimentation. Stuck inside he must find a way out and along the way he will collect documents to reveal more history, writes notes about what what he witnesses and has a small video camera to record everything inside.Fear generates well in games where players cannot defend themselves against threats. 'Outlast' mastered the ability to make players feel emotions of anxiety and panic complimented with intense pursuit moments.  Miles cannot attack the dangerous mad men inside the building. They are much stronger and bigger or armed with deadly weapons. This takes away the players ability to defend themselves and will force players to focus on swift decision making, evasion and hiding in various furniture in rooms or even in the pitch darkness. However, Miles' camera features a night vision light which can be used to navigate in the darkness but drains batteries and players will hope to find them scattered throughout the adventure.The environment is breath takingly stunning and effective in producing an isolated atmosphere. The grain filter provides a realistic look of an old vintage mansion and adds a misty view to where ever you roam. Nightvision is slightly blurred staying true to the realism of a real camera and details provided on body parts are truly gut wrenching. Shine on viscera gives it a fleshy look, well shaped blood stains look remarkably accurate and inmates faces look like actual mutations and burns. Assisting the visuals is a fantastic soundtrack. There isn't too much music in the game, but if you play this game with headphones (I played with a 7.1 surround sound headphones), you will admire the creaking floorboards, footsteps from down the hall, and rain patters on the roof. If you're hiding, music adapts to your surroundings and creates ambience to your current scenario.  You'll hear scratchy violins and deep brass play to intensify the dramatic moment of fear nearby and if you don't feel like screaming, don't worry, Miles was provided with a voice actor who does an amazing job of trying everything he can to breathe quietly while hiding, gasp for air while running and panic while fleeing.The game is only four hours long, but could be much shorter on a second play through. Many players will be tested on their patience to move from place to place while a threat is randomly patrolling and  bravery will be needed when encountering a few various characters who no doubt will have you cornered if you make that wrong step down the hallway or picked an unlucky hiding spot.'Outlast' pushes 'first person horror' to a new depth with its graphic atmosphere, chilling enviroment and incredible detail. It's not a game for the casual player as you'll need to be very good at FPS navigation if you expect to do well in this game.  You won't play this game comfortably regardless of how many lights you leave on and the lingering fear of the unknown never leaves you. You will always walk cautiously and quietly hoping to avoid making the slightest sounds but the game is truly unforgettable and suited for dare devils. Try it with headphones, in the dark and home alone but even if you don't do that, it doesn't matter anyway...You will still be frightened."
