,Recommended,238320,23715541,"Posted: 22 June, 2016",all,RankedUpGamer,"It's a really good horror game and all, but in comparison to other horror games I played it wasn't the scariest. The second half of the game's pacing slows down (after the Trager section) and the story takes a 180. It's probably best to play on the higher difficulty modes as the game is relatively easy and as long as you break line of sight, you're pretty much in the clear. Higher difficulty modes not only make batteries harder to find for your nightvision camcorder, but also makes the enemies more aware. That said, there aren't too many good horror games on Steam and this is one of the best of them. Also when purchasing get the DLC as it is arguably better than the main game itself; the story and pacing is much better, and it resolves the somewhat dissapointing ending of the vanilla game quite well. If you're from the future, this game is a good start if you're getting Outlast 2."
76561198045180742,Recommended,238320,8563791,"Posted: 4 January, 2014",all,Paintmail23,"I decided to pick this game up since it was on a deal during the Christmas Sale, and I also enjoy playing the occasional horror game. Normally horror games don't usually give me many frights and I thought Outlast would be exactly the same as the rest. However, Outlast definitely made me eat my words.You play as the male protagonist Miles Upshur who, according to the start of the game, is a wimp when it comes to fighting. All you're equipped with is a camcorder. No guns, no knives, no weapons whatsoever. You're an unarmed, athletic journalist. Throughout the game you have to accomplish multiple goals in an attempt to escape from the asylum. Most of the time you'll have to sneak around in order to not get brutally murdered, and trust me it sure is brutal. If you get seen, the tense music will kick in, the adrenaline will start rushing around your body, and you'll make your character sprint and jump over obstacles as you head towards the nearest point of safety, whether it's in a locker, under a bed, or hiding under a desk. You'll also try to make sure you have enough batteries for the nightvision feature on your camera, which you can only find lying around. Otherwise you may end up being in the dark, waist deep in sewage, trying to find the way out of the sewer while an enemy, who will rip you apart if he finds you, is hunting you. Trust me, you don't want to have that problem, otherwise dying is probably the best option since it's the quickest way to get your batteries back.In my opinion, trying to sneak around enemies while also trying to complete objectives is the biggest fear factor present the game. i'm sure for most people who have played this game, it's quite nerve-racking when you're trying to see where the enemy is, the music is slowly building up, you move round a corner to get a better view and ""BAM"", the enemy is right in front of you. The panic will be there immediately, you'll turn around to go back into the room and attempt to duke the enemy in order to escape. As soon as you're safe, and the music has settled down, and there's a high chance that the above process may occur again, provoking the same response. There's also many jump scares present in the game, which adds to the fear factor already present when crouching around dark corridors with nightvision as the only light source present, with only your footsteps and breathing being the only sounds to accompany you.I wouldn't say the story of the game is too complicated, but I wasn't really into the story that much. I did care for my character and for the events that caused this place to become what it is now, but the way to sort everything out, to ""fix"" everything, didn't grip me that much (which is the only negative thing I can think of, other than some framerate issues which I think is due to my PC having exactly the minimum system requirements). The documents you find throughout the game will help you understand the backstory, and the good thing about them is they're not a long read, and I've got the same opinion for the notes that you're character makes. Even though I had to run the game on the lowest settings, the enviroment and graphics are very well done and I was certainly impressed considering Red Barrels is a company I've personally never heard of.Overall, the game is very well done and certainly a great horror game. If you're a fan of horror games, then I highly recommend to buy this game, even if it's not on sale. Also a personal thanks to Red Barrels for making a fantastic game, and I can't wait to see the future DLC for this game.Overall rating: 9/10"
