,Recommended,238320,8597369,"Posted: 6 January, 2014",all,HEY I'M GRUM,"After playing many horror games, I was thrilled to find a different game like this. Using a video camera to navigate dark and dank coridors while keeping on the look out for terrifing monsters. I love that feeling because it makes you feel like you're in a horror movie.Game mechanics are done well. Movement is fluid and didn't have a problem transgressing through the horrific areas. Your night vision runs on batteries and the game will give you plently of bateries, although the times where you a running out on your last battery, that is terrifing.The setting is fantastic. You feel a more sense of how ♥♥♥♥ed up this place is as you progress further. With scenes becoming more grotesque as you progress. At time you encounter npcs who actually aren't there to kill you and they provide a good scense for what this place has done to them, enhancing the story.However the one thing that was lacking was the story. I play horror games because of the rich story that is underneath all the scares and increased heart rates. A prime example of this would be the Amnesia games. For Outlast though I felt it was lacking. The story should have been flushed out more. I felt like certain points of the story didn't add up and couldn't remember key points. Your character often writes down his input after witnessing scenes, and I thought they were poorly writen. It is kind of in the style of just some guy off the street, but sense he is a reporter I figured he would have written better. Also in his writing he often reciprecates key points of plot, which is handy, but imo uneeded.Aside from that, this game absoultely excells in its horror. I was absolutely terrified the whole game. No joke. In summary I woud recommend this game highly for it is a unique horror experience with some details that can be over looked"
