,Recommended,238320,12268480,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,FullMetalValkyr,"Pros:-Nice use of nightvision camera, like a found footage movie-Great immersion and storytellingCons:-Repetitive gameplay segments at times-Overused character models for asylum patientsI came out of finishing this game feeling kind of like how I did finishing a game like Bioshock or FEAR and it made me think, I really like story driven horror over scare driven stuff. This game was advertised for it's scariness but at least it had a solid story as well.I really like how this game's story was set up, almost movie like. Right away I felt completely immersed, and I was always keeping myself in check. Should I be exploring in this crazy place, or should I just try and get out? I sometimes felt conflicted however when having to explore for batteries, or trying to find all documents for completionist sakes. Being helpless in this game was justified as the protagonist is a journalist, and having the camera to record the asylum's happenings reminded me of my motivations.Outside of great storytelling, I found myself getting extremely annoyed by certain gameplay segments of the game. There aren't many of these parts, but failing repeatedly just annoyed me to the point where I felt like saying ""ok, that's enough for today"". The basic layout is there is an enemy you really want to avoid partroling, and 2 switches scattered off in different rooms. You flip a switch, this always alerts the enemy on patrol, you hide in a locker, and repeat. I found myself failing a lot to certain enemies, and being chased while being so helpless and having made progress just fried my nerves.I never found myself without batteries in my playthrough, but I probably scared myself a lot anyway sneaking around looking for them. The documents and notes were really well written, I didn't feel like any of them were just fodder. Every note had one really important thing to say, and as someone who doesn't like a ton of reading in a game I didn't mind at all.I really think there is something here for both horror fans and just people looking for good immersive storytelling."
