76561197993917651,Recommended,238320,16671523,"Posted: 24 June, 2015",all,Sidious,"I'm not the kinda guy that plays a lot of horror games. In fact, for a long time, I avoided them as I found them too intimidating. I guess something changed as I got older. After playing games like Alien: Isolation, I started enjoying the genre more. I got some strange kind of satisfaction out of being scared.After reading so many positive things about Outlast, I figured it was worth a shot, especially at the discount price offered during the summer sale. So I bought it.Outlast is not for the timid. I don't have a lot of experience with horror games, but it has to be the scariest game I have played. The fact that you are only equipped with a handheld camera really says it all. You do not face a horde of enemies, but you never know when they show up and when they do, all you can do is run or hide. This creates a tension and claustrophobic atmosphere that makes your visit to the asylum all the more nerve-wrecking.Some of the scenes are extremely graphic, but I assume those who invest in the game are aware of this. The fact that the game world (the asylum) is so grotesque naturally adds to the horror. The game isn't very long (I finished it in about four hours), but the ride is worth every penny. Seeing as the experience is so terrifying, I doubt many people play it through without taking some breaks.The graphics and the sound effects come together really well, lifting an already great game to a higher level. I believe the game is best experienced with headphones as it really immerses the player in the hellhole that is the asylum. However, being a bit of a wimp myself, I used the speakers occasionally. If it gets too scary, playing it during day time also helps!Recommended for fans of the genre."
