,Recommended,238320,8481878,"Posted: 1 January, 2014",all,Insanity_Girl_97,"great game, great surprise. I was bored and wanted to play something new, so i bought it, expecting it to maybe bridge the gap till i find something better. I was presently surprised that this game was better. What makes it great is A: the actual quality of the game, and B: the fact that it was quite scary. The atmosphere is amazing, and amazingly creepy. Lighting and sound are stellar, and i found textures to be above my expectations (although not the best). The setting alone is enough to keep you on edge. You are defensless in an abandoned lunatic asylum. Blood and gore are everywhere, along with crazy people (kind of wild cards, some are trying to murder you, others stand still....not hostile, but suceeding in making you paranoid of them). Jump out scares are spread well throughout the game, but arent over used. There are a few ""find three keys to proceed"" segments. They arent that bad, and as tedious as they can be, the scare factor persists as the enemy stalks through the corridors, waiting and watching. The story is.... well lets just say that it isn't as bad as it could have been, ive seen many worse. To get most of it, you're gonna have to read found documents and scrawled notes. Its decently consistent, not to interesting... putting myself in the shoes of Miles Upshur (the journalist that the game is played through the perspective of), I dont think i would care much about the story anymore either, id be to worried about staying alive. That objective of ""staying alive"", i think is meant to be the focus and this game succeeds at making that a hardship, which is the point."
