76561198074085730,Recommended,238320,10836828,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,Scarkrow,"“The oldest and strongest emotion of mankind is fear, and the oldest and strongest kind of fear is fear of the unknown” - H.P. LovecraftOutlast scares me! Thus far I have been able to play it in 20 minute sessions, not for a lack of time, oh no, I am limited to 20 minutes because I lack the nerve to continue. Alone in a dark room, late at night, my nerve is quickly whittled away.Last night I sat down at 8:45 Pm. I can reasonably play until 11:30. This time I leave the lights on in the room. My wife is sitting on the couch only six feet from me. I can do this!The game play is simple. Walk around pick stuff up, click on buttons and open doors. Oh god, opening doors! I don’t know what’s on the other side, it could me nothing… but it could be… something! If there is something behind the door, I will run and hide… because… those are my options.Run or Hide.I have no gun, no strength, and no Fighting chance! I’m not Marcus Fenix, or Master Chief, hell I’m not even as tough as Luigi. I’m a reporter, a writer, an average Joe. This helplessness it what makes Outlast truly terrifying, helplessness in the face of the dark unknown.The atmosphere is tense and the visuals are clean… well, not clean but crisp, or… Horrifying… Yah, Horrifying. For example, after I walk through a puddle of blood, I trail bloody footprints on the floor behind me.I move through Mount Massive Asylum, carefully traveling from dim lamp to dangling florescent light. I’m forced to travel in the darkness. Terrible, terrible darkness, filled with the ruinous remains of the hospitals contents… and the hospitals staff… and the hospitals Patients…  Patients, some dead… some living. Living patients, pushed past the point of insanity. They are now prone to mindlessly inflicting Violence on anyone they can find. If they can’t find anyone… then they will inflict violence on themselves. Violence has become their total being, and their only form of expression.Darkness is an ever present pressure, forcing itself on me… an inescapable weight on my mind and soul. I’m given one tool to combat the darkness. My ever trusty video camera, with a built in night vision setting. At least… it’s trusty as long as I have enough batteries… which I don’t. I never have enough batteries. I am always looking for more, but while I look, I must conserve the precious juice I have. So when approaching a long dark room, I click my night vision camera on, take a quick glance around the room to get an idea of the layout in my mind. Then I turn off the camera… and I run. I do this again and again, always panicked, always terrified.But it’s not just me that is terrified, it the reporter, the character…he becomes overcome with fear. As we run through the darkness we hear the splash of a puddle at our feat… oh god... It’s blood… we push forward his breath intensifying, becoming erratic… Short gasps, punctuated by trembling exhalations… we stumble over something lying in the blood… We don’t stop to see what it is, because I know what we’ll find… the source of the blood, and the reporter knows it too. His breathing is becoming so intense that it is affecting our vision; the screen sways with each rise and fall of his lungs.  The world around us seems to tremble with a terrible fear.Fear overcomes us. Both the reporter and I are paralyzed with it... unable to face the shadows at the end of the hall. We stand motionless for an eternity… unwilling to move forward… unwilling to face the horrible unknown that fill Mount Massive Asylum… I can’t take it.I save the game and quit. The reporter is on his own. I abandon him to wait in that ever oppressive darkness… I look at the clock…It mockingly displays the time as 9:04 Pm.Sigh…"
