,Recommended,238320,20880675,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,JackxBlack,"TL;DR - 7/10. Lots of jump scares, but as a person prone to them, I was scared. However, it doesn't rely on them only.So I guess I should start off by saying that I am very prone to jump scares. Even though they might not necessarily actually scare me, I will jump in my chair and think about punching the thing that popped out. Luckily I didn't punch my monitor.The game has lots of jump scares. There were times when they were obvious (yeah, dude on the wheelchair, I know you'll stand up to grab me in 0,2s), sometimes a bit less. Sometimes you knew something is going to happen, but not sure exactly what. And I liked that. I know a lot of people think jump scares are the cheapest, least scary things, but they do work on me. So if they work on you too, you might like it as well. On the other hand, thankfully, jump scares were not the only scary thing. The mood was there. Perhaps it's one of the most cliche settings - an asylum overrun by it's patients after a failed experiment - but it was presented very well. The models (as long as you didn't look at them for too long), the environment, the music and the green-ish nightvision postprocess made the (almost) whole experience very heavy and creepy. Overall, the horror part was very good on many levels. One exception is described below, but IT MIGHT BE CONSIDERED A SPOILER.Sadly, aside from being just a horror, it's a horror game. Sadly, that was it's weakest point, that also made the horror part worse, sometimes. Lets start with the least important stuff - there were bugs. Mostly graphical issues of assets popping in on low distance or visibly switching between differing LODs. Sometimes it's also possible to spot how sloppy the artist were, placing buckets that were supposed to be on a table, slightly too low which caused them to clip through it, or by putting some kind of document slightly too low, which caused it to constantly flicker. Another rather technical issue, that made things less scary, were poorly done animations. Multiple times opponents were walkin in a silly way, hovering over terrain etc. The multitude of those issues is a problem, but rather small compared to the others.The biggest faults of this game, gameplay-wise, were it's globally used schemes and mechanics. Almost every level was a sequence of objectives - follow the blood (with jump scares and creepy stuff happening, but nothing lethatl) > figure out that to progress further you need to find/turn on/switch X > get chased by an opponent while doing so > activate the thing that you were supposed to initially, that was inactive > cutscene. Sometimes there was also a ""final chase"" that led usually to climbing a vent. It was extremely repetitive on that side.Opponent's AI is another issue. Their behavior is as predictable as it goes. They move along a very simple, hand-drawn path unless they spot you. Then they chase you, without the ability to catch you as long as you're running, until you get away. Being clumsy dummas they are, they get slowed down a lot by closed doors or obstacles that you jump over, which means you need a couple of those, then some shadow and you're safe. Then they go back to their predefined path. Additionally, some of the obstacles are a safe haven for you - enemies cannot pass narrow passages, climb vents or tall furniture, so you can use them as the area reset if necessary.Last two things that annoyed me were - lack of ability to fight back. I understand that I cannot harm the 2m high, 120kg monster, but why can't I at least try to fight back normal sized, crazy people that were experimented on and are most likely weakened by it, when I am a perfectly healthy male? Why can't I grab anything and make it a weapon? Sadly, that is the concept of horror walkers. Other thing is - if I can parkour so well, climbe ledges etc. why, in order to escape the asylum, won't I just break the window (that has no bars!), climb down and the hell out of there? That was the kind of logical issues that annoyed me.SLIGHT SPOILERS AHEAD, I WILL TRY NOT TO ACTUALLY SPOIL ANYTHING, BUT SOME MIGHT NOT LIKE IT ANYWAY.Final issues. Typically to almost all of the horrors, The Big Evil is no longer scare once you show it. Sadly that was the case in this game as well. Fortunately, despite being present since more or less half of the game, it was only the most important thing in the last chapter. Unfortunately, the last chapter gets in my opinion the worse the further we progress, making the very last couple of seconds of the game not logical, considering what we found out previously. I'm not going to spoil anything more, I just think it contradicts the notes, journals and emails that we have found.END OF SPOILERS.Despite those issues I enjoyed this game, got scared ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ multiple times and I think it's worth the money. If it would be more polished and if the logical issues would be removed, it would be one hell of a game. Sadly it was ""only"" good."
