76561198115837738,Recommended,238320,29001066,Posted: 4 January,all,☣ Assault Potato ☣,Prepare at least 3 pairs of trousers beside you when you play the game. Would be preferable if all of them are brown in colour.
76561197990921513,Recommended,238320,29494154,Posted: 25 January,all,seblecaribou,"The people at Red Barrels are pretty smart developers. Because if, to all apperances, Outlast takes most of its ideas from Amnesia: The Dark Descent (or the Penumbra trilogy) in terms of gameplay ideas, it puts it in a far less elegant environment and lets that dictates the flow of the game. Forget the gracious verbal jousting of Alexander and Daniel and the self-conversation, because your new nickname is now going to be ""little pig"" for almost eight hours - nickname given by a seven foot tall, disfigured killing machine, that rips people heads off with its bare (bear) hands. That is the ambiance here. Extremely stereotypical creepos in lieu and place of normal human beings with mental illness inhabit the biggest asylum you've ever seen, complete with a prison section, a church, sewers and all that with the flimsiest electrical instalation conceivable. The first steps in Outlast are made to freak you out with a pretty violent imagery, dismantled bodies, blood all over the place and all rendered in a surprisingly gorgeous engine for a team that small. You, a journalist that clearly as suicidal tendencies, simply follow the remarkably well paced and extremely linear story to uncover what went wrong.So the gameplay is pretty much Amnesia. Except you are not finding tinderboxes to light up the place or oil to replenish your lantern; you are only searching for batteries to fill up your video-camera that happens to have a night-vision mode. Because the protagonist is filming all this. Despite the brutality of what he sees and suffers, he keeps on filming. You have the choice to play the game without looking in the camera, but the zoom-in and out and NV are your saving graces here to navigate the dark hallways. It also is your only advantage over the enemies in the game, that consists in the same kind of lethal stalkers that Amnesia had. You can't bit them, except for scripted events that the game will explicitely show you. So your only chance at surviving is finding the next door or crouching in the darkest place possible. Which is, again like Amnesia, a great way to create tension, forcing the player to either listen to the psychopathic a**hole in complete darkness, or looking where he is through the lens of the camera, wasting precious batery that could help finding the next place.The story is delivered through environmental clues as much as the classic notes from RE. But contrary to Amnesia or RE, Outlast has some NPCs that can give short but efficient exposition.And overall, I think that ""efficient"" is the best term to describe Outlast. It isn't a ground breaking game in terms of mechanics, that pretty much consists in light exploration, navigation, and light stealth. It isn't ground breaking in terms of art direction. It isn't amazing in terms of story either. But each elements is really well done, and well done enough that it creates tension from beginning to end. You are not going to be surprised by a second playthrough, since due to the linearity of the game you will see 95% of it in one run. But you will have some fun spooky moments. Not the lingering uneasiness of a Silent Hill, but a cathartic stream of build-up and pay-off, jumscares and stressful shunks of gameplay. It is pretty light in terms of mechanics but never to its disadvantage. Simply put, it is a fun horror game.TR;DLProof that linearity and scripted gameplay aren't doomed to be associated with sh*tty triple A yearly releases, Outlast is the best example of a good (if not great with its excellent ""Whistleblower"" DLC) spook-house. The atmosphere is really neatly built thanks to an efficient art direction that aims somewhere between realism for the technical aspect and its decorum and over-the-top representation of insane people for the occupants. Not the most replayable horror game to boot, but a great and fun ride nonetheless."
