,Recommended,238320,12471063,"Posted: 12 October, 2014",all,TheColorUrple,"In Resident Evil, your character was a special forces hero - professionally trained in combat, courageous beyond measure, and on an IMPORTANT MISSION. The mansion you escape to at the very beginning of the game is a safe haven compared to the dangerous woods surrounding it. It makes sense that, rather than try to escape, your heroes explore the mansion's twisted corridors. When those warm, luxurious locales eventually lead to an underground laboratory at the heart of a zombie virus outbreak, it also makes sense that they would blow everything up and finish the job.Outlast, for all of its merits, doesn't feature a character who seems to understand his peril. The first hour of the game is nearly perfect, introducing you to the horror at just the right pace, leading to a deep sense of immersion and utter fear in ways that no other game has yet done for me. It was so successful in making me feel like I was there, in fact, that I truly, deeply, wanted to get the ♥♥♥♥ out. It was too much. This is not a place some idiot with a video camera should be hanging out.Think about this story grounded in reality. An incredibly brave journalist walks into a seemingly abandoned mental hospital, only to capture actual footage of a couple of psychotic patients and a few mutilated bodies. He spends a half hour walking around, realizes this is a dangerous and completely insane place, breaks the nearest window, and jumps out of it, running as fast as he can to safety. He submits the footage to his boss the following morning, leading to a full government investigation within hours, garnering national media coverage in the process. The journalist is now borderline famous, gives a late-night interview with Conan O'Brien about his harrowing experience, and is set for a very lucrative career.You would have to be a complete goddamn lunatic to spend more than a minute in that place without a weapon or several well-armed friends. I found myself wishing I could open a window and just jump the ♥♥♥♥ out, risk a couple of broken legs in exchange for not getting mauled to death by some lunatic. The last thing I would do is Resident Evil.Yet this is what you do - delve deeper and deeper into the mystery, against increasingly insurmountable and supernatural forces, all for....video footage? To be honest, I'm not sure. I completely disconnected with the character.It's fitting then, that as soon as I started figuring out the mechanics of the game - running, hiding, exploiting the AI - I began playing Outlast like a video game. Just another video game. A good one, don't get me wrong - but that unique immersive experience was mostly gone, and I was left enjoying the story, the setting, and the ridiculous plot that (MINOR SPOILER) doesn't really tie up too nicely (END MINOR SPOILER), as a passive observer.I liked the game, but I would have loved the experience."
