,Recommended,238320,17604279,"Posted: 18 August, 2015",all,Mint,"What's to say about this game that every webcamming Youtuber hasn't said in the past few years. There really isn't a whole lot so I'll just be straight forward. Outlast is SCARY! It has a slightly different take on horror with some of it's mechanics, which is nice but, even to this day I still see the game as nothing but an Amnesia knock off. I'm sorry but Amnesia and Cry of Fear are still going to be my top favorite horror games that I've ever played, but back to Outlast.Outlast definitely spooked me the first time I played it, but at times it felt a bit more suspenseful than scary, which if that's what they were going for they did a great job at it. It's definitely terrifying/exhilarating to be chased by crazy inmates or Chris Walker and it's definitely not fun to hide in the locker until an enemy goes away, while trying to conserve your battery life on your camera. Speaking of which, the first time I played this game I had a big issue when it came to finding batteries and trust me I explored as much as I could (which could be the reason for why my batteries died out so fast).One big problem I had with this game came to the puzzle sections and it got disappointing of how simple they were. This is where they failed for trying to captivate what Amnesia did. In Amnesia you're required to collect objects and mix them with other objects and use them on other objects and to solve puzzles (it was basically a first-person point and click adventure), all while trying to reserve your oil and sneak past enemies. Outlast on the other hand requires you to sneak past enemies and press some buttons, flip a switch or collect some item and make it back to safety without getting killed. While the puzzles for the game are not innovative, surviving encounters with enemies definitely comes close to a whole new level of scariness for me. 1st) the hiding spaces that you have are pretty limited which isn't very fun to handle, 2nd) it's almost beyond pointless to turn off your night vision in the game, especially when you need to see enemies from a distance, 3rd) the sound design is exellent and 4th) there were a lot of times in this game for I literally thought I was not going to be able to progress past enemy because of how scared I was or because of their walking patterns being completely random/unpredictable. While that may sound like a good thing it really isn't, there was one time where I had to hide under a bed and I was completely trapped in this hallway because Chris freaking Walker kept walking past the hallway into a dead end every 15 seconds and gave me little time to escape, it was complete luck that I got out of that situation on un-hurt, which could be a fault in game design, but I'm going to put this on myself because I'm a pretty big wimp when it comes to this stuff despite the fact and Amnesia: The Dark Descent and Cry of Fear are both some of my most favortie games ever.So in my opinion Outlast doesn't do everything perfectly, but in the end I still felt really scared which is what the game overall meant to do.Basically, I enjoyed my time with Outlast and I'm pretty excited for Outlast 2!"
