76561198134081802,Recommended,238320,23352893,"Posted: 2 June, 2016",all,tushie moskow,It cured my constipation
,Recommended,238320,19002129,"Posted: 10 November, 2015",all,Scrubsauce,"If I could sum up Outlast in one word, it would be, uh, I dunno...one word? Hmm, I'm drawing a blank so I'll stick with...sticky?  Oh man that's a terrible pun...  I suppose that in the literal sense, the walls, and floor, and all the gore splattered surfaces of the inner chambers of the asylum are probably way sticky.  In the metaphorical sense, some of the more intense imagery has stuck with me weeks after I completed my playthrough of the main story.  Wait- that's the word, intense!Outlast has the usual rising and falling of action you'd expect from a horror-thriller.  You'll spend most of your time on the run or hiding from the enemy AI.  The enemies are pretty decently varied, considering the setting being a locked-down asylum.  Red Barrels still manages to make a nice lineup of crazies trying to murder you without falling into the trappings of other horror games where the ""fear"" tends to dissipate from the enemy becoming too familiar to the player.  The saving grace for the enemies of Outlast is there's no question of their intent, if they get ahold of you they will beat you to a bloody pulp, and in some cases tear you to pieces.  So like any air-breathing human you'll be motivated to RUN.Thankfully there's some breaks in the ""omg omg, please don't let him catch up to me"" bits to do a little exploring of the various sections of the asylum you tour.  Playing the role of a reporter, your goal is to document some shady stuff going down in the mountains of Colorado.  The plot exposes itself slowly via minor tidbits uttered from NPC's, and various notes scattered around the game, but the moment you enter the asylum you know something is wrong.  Red Barrels doesn't create a traditional horror atmosphere, instead opting for what I'm more inclined to refer to as terror.  Yeah, there's a difference and that's probably subjective, but I digress.  The graphics are gorgeous, especially for not being a AAA experience.  Outlast has almost set the bar too high for me, making other Indie horror titles seem kind of fake, or cartoony.My favorite parts of the mechancics are the things that Outlast does that I haven't experienced in a horror game before.  The ability to pick a hiding place, under a bed, in a locker, etc. is a welcome change to the Amnesia-style ""hide in the dark until the music stops"", albeit that's still a perfectly valid strategy.  The thing is, the hiding spaces aren't always safe, and those moments where the bad guy enters the room hot on your tail, and decides to check the ONE bed you elected to hide under are terrifying and will send you running back out the door yelling ""NOPE NOPE NOPE"".  The other main defining characteristic of Outlast is the camera.  Keeping it running will expand upon the story by creating notes by the protagonist and giving their take on the events.  There's also a night vision mechanic that requires traditional resource management fans of Amnesia and Resident Evil will be familiar with.  If you run out of batteries, you won't be able to see in the dark at all, but thankfully neither can the baddies, making the pitch black areas a double-edged sword.  The only part of the gameplay I wasn't very in favor of was the reptition of certain sequences where I knew exactly what I needed to do to progress the plot (usually consisting of turn X valves or pull Y levers to unlock new area), but was having to constantly deal with the hassle of a big baddie trying to squish my head under his big thumping boots.The story nearly becomes irrelevant later in the game because I just so desperately wanted the main character to escape and have a happy ending.  The plot stays competent to the end, though I can see some of the explanations of the more mysterious parts rubbing true horror fans the wrong way with its reliance on more traditional sci-fi tropes.  If you're looking for a more realistic, adrenaline packed NOPE-fest then Outlast is probably a good call."
