76561198034140289,Recommended,238320,27601618,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Peter Moore,"+ Great atmosphere and a few jump scares.+ Intense on Insane mode difficulty which doesn't allow for saving or check points.+ Night vision looks really nice.  Batteries are scarce on Insane mode.  You'll stop dead in your tracks as enemies pop out of the shadows before your eyes.+ Great for speedrunning.+ The Whistleblower DLC (sold seperately) is well made and pushes the envelope further than the base game.  Outlast's DLC is a worthwhile expansion if you want more.- Mostly linear.  Outlast has been described as a ""virtual ghost train"".  Not entirely fair as there are various rooms, hiding places, and strategies you can use to survive, but in the vast majority of cases, there's one path out of each danger zone.- Story is mostly cliched, typical horror stuff.- Unskippable cutscenes.  One mid-game cutscene lasts around four minutes.  Great the first time you see it, not so much if you're constantly replaying on Insane mode.- Quite short.Personal recommendation:  As you can probably tell, I think the value here is in Insane mode.  Play it on Insane mode until you complete it, then go achievement hunting on the lower difficulties if need be.  The game really thrives when death is something you fear.  You don't get that with checkpoints.  The Whistleblower is also a worthwhile addition if you want more, especially at its regular sale price."
