76561198191909877,Recommended,238320,17594466,"Posted: 17 August, 2015",all,NightSiren13,"What started for me as watching someone play through this game and laughing hysterically at their reactions would quickly turn into breath-stealing panic once I started playing the game myself. I knew from the start that Outlast was an intense horror game and I was excited to play it myself, but I didn't quite realize the level of immersiveness until I put on headphones. Instantly, I was placed in Miles' shoes with my camera in hand, creeping cautiously through corridors and around corners, praying my batteries wouldn't run out while I was lost in the darkness being chased by the mutated criminally insane and hearing his heartbeat and breathing react to the stresses of the various situations you find yourself in throughout the game environment. I would soon find my own heart beating in synch with his, my breath catching in my throat while my eyes were glued to the screen with paranoid alertness to the horrors that surrounded me. It would take pulling my headphones off and looking around my room to pull me back into reality and remember that it was just a game.....an incredible, horrific and well-done game.So much can be said about this game that can sum up my approval, but I will limit it to as few as possible; with a storyline that isn't so obvious and characters that can be as unpredictable as youd'd expect real lunatics to be, the first-person perspective and protagonist reactions make this a game that truly transports you there and terrifies you to your core. I can only imagine what this would be like if played on the Oculus Rift....10/10 in my book, with the DLC included. Two different perspectives during the same timeline and both equally as disturbing. Love it."
