,Recommended,238320,28802919,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,james.purcell,"At first I played this game just to the first enemy encounter, and the checkpoint save system frustrated me so much that I shelved it for a year, coming back to it occasionally only to get frustrated again. My logic with shelving it was that, yes the game is terrifying, but I anticipated that the game would continue to have this pattern right up to the end: Play the game, be completely terrified, die. Go back to last checkpoint. Less terrified now. Die. Back to last checkpoint. Game isn't scary anymore because you know what's going to happen. Advance to next stage. Rinse and repeat.I was wrong.The reason I was wrong is that there are a lot of checkpoint saves. A lot. The game saves really frequently. I am so glad I finally decided to just beat this game, because it's about the most disturbing and one of the scariest games I've ever played. Like, holy crap guys. Why are you even reading this review when you could be buying, installing and playing this game with the lights out and headphones in. I wish I could wipe my memory of this game, just so I could play it again.The DLC ""Whistleblower"" is just as terrifying as the main game, but even more disturbing. It's about half the length. Definitely worth it.Start out on hard mode, as normal mode just means the normal enemies can hit you 5 times with a baseball bat with a nail in it before you die, which pulls you right out of the immersion because that's ridiculous. Just don't get seen or hit, which is completely managable."
