,Recommended,238320,12106738,"Posted: 15 September, 2014",all,TJX2045,"9 out of 10:Some of the original Silent Hill games, the first F.E.A.R. game were among the few horror games to truly scare the $%@! out of me and make me really uncomfortable.  Now that I've finally played Outlast (which I luckily got during the summer sale) and beaten it today, I can add it to the list of games to actually scare me and not use only cheap jump startles like some other ""horror"" games (because being startled is different than being SCARED).There are definitely jump scares in this game, but the real terror comes in the tension in the atmosphere and the build up.  After the jump scare, the terror is made worse when you find out what is chasing you or see it up close.  One of the most terrifying moments I had in this game was in the beginning when I was being chased by the first prisoner and I decided to look over my shoulder.  Turns out this was a terrible idea as he was RIGHT BEHIND ME and I screamed bloody murder.Silent Hill is the only other horror game that actually made me scream out loud before this.  Normally I just curse a lot when I play horror games or make a loud gasp, but even in times where I tried my hardest to bite my lips together and stifle my sound, the game somehow still got me to scream.  The way the atmosphere and the ambient noise #%%s with your mind is absolutely insane.  But I love it and no matter how scared I was, this game was definitely worth it.The only negative I can think of is It will be frustrating and you will die many times.  You may even become a little numb to certain scenarios once you have to repeat them after death, but the levels and areas have enough differences between them to keep you on your toes the entire time.  Claustrophobic?  The game has it.  Agoraphobic?  It has that too.  Something that might be considered negative by others would be the battery duration, but unless you're playing on Hard or higher, most of the time you can find plenty of batteries if you're not too chicken to explore.Regardless, this game is worth it and you must play it the only way that I believe it should be experienced:  In complete darkness, with a pair of headphones (surround sound or amplified gaming headphones recommended) and a controller.  Make sure you crank the volume up and you're in for a wild ride."
