76561197970737987,Recommended,238320,25549744,"Posted: 17 September, 2016",all,StretchNorth,"Reviews and reviewers make me angry. Don't read this. Buy the game and make your own mind up. Then have a good think about how the creative industries as a whole use reviewing to part you from your cash. Theft really is not the word for it.I like a good scare. This game is good at scaring. However it is not the immersive terrifying experience that  some (paid?) reviewers have been prone to bill it as. The best games ever produced had fantastic scripts written by very talented people balanced with superior game mechanics that match the intended experience. This feels like its a level below that. It relies on in your face frights and atmospheric noises just a little too much whilst neglecting, a little too much, a truly terrifying script/game design that will fully engage your imagination.After a few hours the scared stiff breathing of the main protagonist gets more than a little annoying. The inablity to fight back is, to begin with, a treat to get the adrenalin running. However I'm often brought out of the game immersion to simply get annoyed at the noises he makes along with the lack of retaliation or even... I don't know! maybe effin knock something over behind you as you run or hit that ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ with a plank in the dark as he comes through the door. DUUUUDE do something to survive you moron. I have more than once died trying to get through an open door in a hurry but then again at this point I barely care if he lives or dies. Terror has been suspended by annoyance.One immersion breaking point is watching the characters move in the dark, sure footed and as if the room is brightly lit.It often becomes apparent that the other characters follow a rigid script that can be exploited, until you realise that it's not exploiting, this is simply the game. AI feels like it is almost non existent. The plot feels like it too obviously advances in a number of set scenes. You intuitively know when you are safe to run around because you know that you have just 'finished' the latest scene.This could have been the single most scary game ever released but it is unable to sustain fear due to there being so many immersion breaking points.All of the parts are there, quality graphics, quality sound, quality programming but it misses on bringing all this together. Not by far, but enough to make this game good, not great. Once again hype and fanboy aggression trumps fact and for some ruins the expectation.Having said this the game is very playable. Play it in a dark room, with decent sound then engage your imagination and it should give you some nice chills/scares.Finally it should be noted that having the camcorder light as your only real tool is not very original. It is a variation on a number of games, perhaps the most obvious being Alan Wake. Its inclusion produces a wry smile to those of us who have played video games on dozens of platforms, for decades. We just keep seeing the same music, films and games coming around in shiny new packages to suit the next generation. Sad really but a lesson we all learn as we transition into grumpy old ............7/10"
