76561197993446358,Recommended,238320,13332159,"Posted: 12 December, 2014",all,TheOneTrueD,"DISCLAIMER: This reviewer has not played the Whistleblower DLC and therefore, their rating and comments on the game will not be accounting for this content. This review will contain no spoilers for neither plot nor story.-TRIAL AND ERROR SIMULATOR-CHASE AND RUN AWAY SIMULATOR-♥♥♥♥♥♥ AI AND HIDING SIMULATORIf you buy this game, prepare for sub-par gameplay. You have little  to no influence over whether you survive an enemy encounter or not - as aforementioned, in obnoxious CapsLock, when you encounter an enemy, all you can do is run away  - which is all well and good, right? ""Many games, especially of the Horror genre, do this"", you say.The short answer would be yes, but the problem is that there is often ONE PATH to slip away from an enemy, often involving opening doors and closing them again, and it's IMPOSSIBLE to tell whether the door is actually locked or not, meaning you'll die 19 times to one enemy because you just happened to ""make the wrong guess"" as to which way was the right one.In general, you have very little control over the main character's actions; oftentimes, when tense action is happening, it involves first-person cutscenes of the events, with you just sitting there watching. In essence, all you have control over in this game is:-Movement (limited due to the aforementioned)-Picking up certain items (involving batteries for your camcorder, files/journals and certain progress-vital items)That's it. Quite dull.""But Shape - why are you recommending this game then?""Because of three major points, which, in my opinion, easily compensates for the aforementioned flaws:1) The plot: Many Horror games, and especially movies for that matter, have an incredibly dull and boring plot, and only get small points for cheap jump scares and similar tropes. This game is not one of those. At all. While there certainly are jump scares, the plot of this story is easily one of the most interesting, fascinating and most well-fleshed out ones I've experienced in any Horror game, being up there with classic Silent Hill, classic Resident Evil and the first Amnesia (note that I'm not comparing this plot to those games, it is in no way similar, it just delivers the same amount of quality). It puts you in the setting, ranging from fairly peaceful-looking to fishy to ""what the ♥♥♥♥ is going on?"" to batshit insanity. And it does so in a very smooth way, with no try-hard scares and forced plotting like you occasionally see in other games of the genre.2) The design: This is mainly focused on characters - both their aesthetic appearance and their personality. You are presented with a wide array of interesting characters, all done in a way where you're never quite sure whom to trust and whom to oppose. You're going to be falling through the cracks attempting to figure out who is good and who is bad - in other words, the characters are what presents this great plot in its own way: a complete and utter moral greyzone.3) The atmosphere: The story unfolds in an old mental hospital, and you might think it's cliché, that you've seen this all before, that it is an overused setting. And you might be right - but assuredly, it has never been presented in the way Outlast manages to: grim darkness in every corner, the palette of clinical instruments and brushed steel paired with horrible gore and bloodstains, spiced with deranged freaks walking around everywhere, unpredictably, makes the raw experience of this game easily worth both your time and your money.Overall, I would certainly recommend this game - if you manage to read this review while there's a sale, there is ABSOLUTELY NO EXCUSE not to buy this game if you're a die-hard Horror fanatic like me, and you've got money in your pocket. And don't worry about my initial remarks about the gameplay: they're effortlessly overshadowed by the great story, you're in for."
