,Recommended,238320,22631487,"Posted: 25 April, 2016",all,FinalQuake,"""Nanomachines, son.""~Alan Turing's long lost geriatric homosexual bald Nazi loverAbsolute, Unbridled StupidityThat's the only way to describe this game. I really hope this game was intentionally written as an absurdist comedy, because it's hilarious.Outhouse tells the story of Miles Upshur Without A Paddle, an investigative journalist who recieves an email from""10260110756@mutemail.com""and decides to still take the contents of said email as fact. The email literally contains the line ""Terrible things happening there. Don't understand it."" and instructs Miles to head to Mount Massive BS Asylum where he'll come face to face with the ""terrible things"" that lurk within. These 'terrible things"" include, but are not limited to: A crazy bald guy that thinks he's a priest, a pair of crazy bald twins that run around nude and make you envious of their massive dongs, a crazy bald guy whose size is an anatomic impossibility, a crazy bald guy wielding giant scissors, a crazy bald ghost, and Alan Turing's long lost geriatric homosexual bald Nazi lover. The developers allege that this is a survival horror game.Outlast was written and developed by people whom I would describe as competent idiots. Mechanically speaking, their game is well done. It suffers from no obvious technical errors, and while the environments are generic, they are still well designed. The gameplay isn't even remotely scary and I struggle to see how someone could be scared of this, but we don't really play these games for the sake of playing them; we play them for their story, and the story here makes no damn sense whatsoever.This is where the ""idiots"" part of ""competent idiots"" comes into play. The story is so unbelievably stupid that it blew my mind and kept me laughing for days. I'm honestly at a loss for words. It's incredibly original, I'll give it that, but only because it's so stupid there simply isn't a way it could've been done before, or ever again for that matter. I'm struggling to come up with a way to explain it. It's like the video game version of M. Night Shyamalan's the Village. It's best if you just experience it for yourself.In ConclusionOutlast is a mess you need to play. I'm most certainly not recommending this game for the right reasons, but that's okay, because a recommendation is still a recommendation."
