,Recommended,238320,31146125,Posted: 14 April,all,December Man,"*This is a review of both the base game and the DLC*Entertaining game, with an enjoyable camera gimmick, having to record to unlock the character's insight into the events he witnesses. The story was obviously created around the setting, not the other way around - first, they decided to place he game inside an insane asylum, then they built a story around it. It starts relatively down to Earth, only to introduce a supernatural element which is handwaived as not being paranormal in nature because a character said so - literally.It's atmospheric, but it's not scary in the least, especially when you discover the main character is essentially an Olympic level athlete and can run for an indefinite amount of time leaving the antagonists behind with little effort (not only that, at some pointhe loses his fingersand does not bother to stop the bleeding or get himself a bandage at any point in time - he's that ""badass""). The only thing that might startle you are the jumpscares which are the cheapest of the cheap. The first one you encounter was the cheapest jumpscare I have seen in years - it's the level of those old troll flash games with extremely loud sounds and ""scary"" images hidden inside of them. It's also repetitive and uses probably every horror game cliche ever.At its best the game is not disturbing and horrifying - it's disguisting and revolting (it tries so hard to shock you that I find it pretty amusing; it's the ultimate edgelord game: lots of blood and gore, cannibalism, necrophilia, masturbation, genital mutilation - all with the subtlety of USSR). It's the Hostel of video games and Red Barrels are Eli Roth. It's not necessarily a bad thing, but Eli Roth's movies are not revered as masterpieces of horror, but what they are: gore / exploitation flicks.I don't know if I should recommend it or not. If the developer's intentions were to shock their audience, they succeeded. If they attempted to create a genuinely scary experience which doesn't rely purely on jumpscares, they failed spectacularly. By the end of the day though, no matter what they tried to do, I was entertained (in a guilty pleasure, so-bad-it's-good sort of way) so thumbs up it is.<edit>I would like to add that I'm going to be disappointed if the sequel doesn't have something akin to baby eating - I mean at this point this is the only way this developer can one up themselves.</edit>"
