,Recommended,238320,7847343,"Posted: 30 November, 2013",all,"God, owner of the Universe","THIS GAME SCORES [0 1 | 2 *3*] = ~88% (75%-100%)Wow. What this game does, it does very very well. The elements that come into play are in great balance. And the graphics - textures, models, colors, light, visual noise, the two camera views, ... - are all top notch. There were also all kinds of physical exercise: Walking, running, crouching, jumping, climbing ladders, climbing up ledges, squeezing through small openings, walking on small ledges with the back to the wall, hanging from ledges and moving sideways - and all the time, you can see your body, fully rendered, and the ""camera"" moves in a very natural way, feels a bit like the Dark Engine games (Thief Gold etc.). If they'd make an actual Thief game like this, it would be a really great product.I paid 6.45€ for Outlast don't regret it in the least. I've only played 2-3 hours yet and just arrived in the sewers, the experience so far has had great variety.I have read in another critique about flaws, and I agree: While the breathing-effect that expresses your panic is quite realistic (Imagine how you'd actually feel in those situations, hiding behind something while personified pain and death walk right in front of you, and you don't know what they'll do.), it's somewhat loud and, in combination with the very well done music effects (which I believe are synthetic instead from a real orchestra, but it took me over an hour to realize that), impedes on your acoustical awareness a bit, so it's sometimes hard to listen to footsteps and such. There should have been a key for holding your breath like in sniper games, that would have fit very well in this game. Also, the breathing indeed sometimes gives away if there's a dangerous guy nearby, even though I myself hadn't realized that yet, but that's only a very minor problem.Then there was the complaint about the formulaic game-play: Do some tasks, and while you're at it, a hazard will be around that you have to avoid. I now recognize this in the sewers, because so far it hadn't occurred enough for a pattern to emerge. I don't know if this will be a problem, but even if so: Then just play the game in bursts of at most 3 hours (which isn't exactly little - then again, the checkpoints are not too close by, and ""save & exit"" does NOT exactly what it says, so better play until you saw ""saving..."" in the left bottom corner), and you should be fine. It must also be said that this formulaic approach is only one layer of the gameplay, and the other layers are very well done. So, this complaint, too, is only minor. You really have to experience the game: It's so well done that any flaws you might find can only be considered to be nitpicking.There is no FOV (field of view) slider, but you can easily and lastingly adjust the FOV by editing a file. Make a duplicate ofC:\Users\[your user name]\Documents\My Games\Outlast\OLGame\Config\OLGame.iniand then edit the original. Search for ""fov"", you'll find ""DefaultFOV="" and ""RunningFOV="" (the latter being slightly higher than the former). I set mine to 120 and 130, which is not as high as it sounds, the game interprets them a bit differently from what we're used to. Save the file, done. Use any value you like. You could also change ""CamcorderNVMaxFOV="" and ""CamcorderMaxFOV="", but I didn't. I found the claustrophobic too-narrow default FOV of the video camera to be ok, even though I am an absolute FOV-Nazi. There are other tweaks you might want to try, but I ignored them so far. I got all my tips here:http://steamcommunity.com/app/238320/discussions/0/846963710902292389/So. All in all: A great game in the category and quality (maybe even higher) of ""Amnesia: The Dark Descent""."
