,Recommended,238320,12059873,"Posted: 10 September, 2014",all,Fishzerg,"I strongly recommend this game to anyone for insane atmosphere, immersion, bad♥♥♥♥♥gameplay, great story and characters. Play it even if you are scared of the dark, because once you have seen what is in Outlast, you will never be afraid again, as nothing that horrorful can exist in real life.Outlast is the master of horror games. I finished it and it lingers in my head still, both the story and the characters. You know that you have played a good h o r r o r game when you think to yourself that you wil never play this again. Because it is that horrifying.Game should be played in complete darkness and with proper headphones, or at least a good surround system.The game masters mostly everything. It is very cleverly built. The usage of light and complete dark is used to an extreme advantage here, and done so very well. There are lots of surprising elements. Your character doesn't have any weapons and can do only two things: run or hide, often a combination of both. But still, when escaping an area successfully you get this great feeling of mastering something: you survived.The scares in this game are endless. What I loved the most was that some of them were pretty silly, the game obviously mocking and laughing at you for scaring you. That said, the game is mostly very serious and deals with the theme of insane asylum in a proper ""not safe for life"" way, but it doesn't take itself too seriously through certain funny moments.Monster and scare-wise Outlast is like a hyperactive Amnesia. What I loved about it is that certain enemies are the same characters that keep following you through the whole game, trying to catch you. This adds alot to the immersion, which otherwise is top notch.My only tiny minus side was that a few areas were too dark, even with light turned on in-game. Feels like I missed some detail there, but this happened only in around 5% of the game."
